The paper discusses graph partitioning methods for distributed computation, which falls under the category of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC). The specific focus on natural graphs and the use of power-law distribution suggests a connection to Network Science (cs.SI) and Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS). The use of streaming algorithms and online partitioning suggests a connection to Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI). Finally, the evaluation of the proposed method against state-of-the-art baselines suggests a connection to Machine Learning (cs.LG).
